<h2>What Is Codependency?</h2>
<p>Codependency describes a pattern of relating characterised by excessive focus on others' needs, feelings, and problems at the expense of one's own; difficulty identifying and expressing one's own needs; self-worth that depends on being needed; and a tendency to enable problematic behaviour in others rather than allowing natural consequences.</p>

<p>The term originated in addiction treatment — it initially described family members of people with substance use disorders who became enmeshed with and organised around the addicted person's behaviour. It has since broadened to describe relationship patterns more generally that involve self-abandonment in the service of other-focus.</p>

<h2>How Codependency Develops</h2>
<p>Codependency is typically learned in families where:</p>
<ul>
  <li>A parent had a mental illness, addiction, chronic illness, or emotional instability that made them unpredictable</li>
  <li>A child's needs were consistently deprioritised or dismissed</li>
  <li>Emotional attunement was conditional — love available when the child behaved in certain ways, withheld otherwise</li>
  <li>Being needed was the primary way of receiving attention and connection</li>
  <li>Conflict was dangerous, and keeping the peace was the child's responsibility</li>
</ul>

<p>Children in these environments learn to scan their caregivers for emotional states, anticipate and manage others' feelings, and subordinate their own needs to the family system. In adulthood, these adaptations replay in relationships.</p>

<h2>Signs of Codependency</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Difficulty saying no — fear of disapproval or abandonment</li>
  <li>Feeling responsible for others' emotions and outcomes</li>
  <li>Deriving identity and self-worth from being needed</li>
  <li>Difficulty identifying what you want or need separate from others</li>
  <li>Staying in relationships that are consistently damaging</li>
  <li>Enabling: covering for others' behaviour, making excuses, preventing consequences</li>
  <li>Neglect of your own needs, health, or relationships</li>
  <li>Anxiety or guilt when you prioritise yourself</li>
</ul>

<h2>How Therapy Helps</h2>

<h3>Rebuilding a Sense of Self</h3>
<p>People with codependent patterns often have limited access to their own needs, desires, and emotions — these were suppressed or never developed. Therapy involves the slow work of identifying what you actually feel, what you actually want, and what your own values are, separate from others' expectations.</p>

<h3>Attachment Healing</h3>
<p>Codependency is rooted in insecure attachment — typically anxious attachment characterised by fear of abandonment and hypervigilance to others' emotional states. Attachment-focused therapy addresses the early relational patterns that made this necessary and develops more secure relational capacity.</p>

<h3>Boundary Work</h3>
<p>Boundaries — the ability to say no, to have separate needs, to tolerate others' disappointment — feel dangerous to codependent people. They were dangerous in the original family context. Therapy involves understanding why, grieving that, and developing the ability to set limits from choice rather than fear.</p>

<h3>Enabling and Relationship Patterns</h3>
<p>Therapy specifically addresses enabling patterns — not as moral failing but as understandable responses to anxiety. The work involves tolerating the discomfort of allowing natural consequences and detaching with love rather than control.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Is codependency a real clinical diagnosis?</strong><br/>
It's not a formal DSM diagnosis but is a widely used and clinically meaningful concept describing a recognisable pattern with evidence-based treatment. It often appears alongside trauma, anxious attachment, and personality patterns.</p>

<p><strong>Can you be codependent in non-romantic relationships?</strong><br/>
Yes. Codependent patterns appear in family relationships (adult children of addicted or mentally ill parents), friendships, and workplace relationships. The dynamic doesn't require a romantic context.</p>

<p><strong>What if I'm the one being "enabled"?</strong><br/>
People with addiction, mental illness, or chronic irresponsibility who are surrounded by enabling often don't recover until enabling stops. If you suspect this is your situation, individual therapy — for you — is still the right first step.</p>

